# SALESFORCE LOGGING & MONITORING — Implementation Guide for Junior Developers

---

## 1. Overview & What You Need to Know

This guide walks you through implementing a logging and monitoring solution for Salesforce. Think of it as setting up a security camera system for your Salesforce environment — you want to know who is coming in, what they are doing, and get alerted if anything looks suspicious.

> **📌 The Simple Version:** Your job is to connect Salesforce to Microsoft Defender for Cloud Apps (DfCA). Once connected, Defender will automatically pull Salesforce activity logs, analyse them, and alert you when something looks wrong.

### What is the MVP Approach?

MVP = Minimum Viable Product. Your senior has kept this simple. The plan is:

1. Set up the Salesforce + Microsoft Defender for Cloud Apps integration
2. Start monitoring the logs available now (out of the box)
3. Review what gaps exist and decide if Salesforce Shield is needed for deeper logging

> **💡 What is Salesforce Shield?** Shield is a premium Salesforce add-on that unlocks detailed audit trails, field-level encryption, and event monitoring (like tracking every click a user makes). It costs extra, so you evaluate if it's needed after the MVP.

### Two Key Tools You Will Work With

| Tool | What it Does |
|---|---|
| **Salesforce** | Your CRM platform — it generates logs of all user activity, logins, API calls, data exports, etc. |
| **Microsoft Defender for Cloud Apps (DfCA)** | A security tool that connects to Salesforce, collects its logs, and monitors for suspicious behaviour. Think of it as the "brain" that analyses the camera footage. |

