## 3. Salesforce Log Types — What Is Available

### Out-of-the-Box Logs (No Extra Licence Needed)

| Log Type | What It Captures | Which Events It Covers |
|---|---|---|
| **Login History** | All login attempts, source IP, timestamp, login type (UI vs API) | Login events, failed logins, breakglass use |
| **Setup Audit Trail** | 6 months of admin changes — user creation, permission changes, security settings | Privilege escalation, security policy changes |
| **API Usage Logs** | API calls made by integrations and users | Bulk API requests, suspicious API behaviour |
| **Event Log Files (ELF)** | Daily CSV files covering ~50 event types — logins, reports, API calls, SOQL queries | Broad coverage — the main log source |

> **💡 Note on Event Log Files:** ELF is one of the most powerful standard log sources in Salesforce. It produces CSV files daily. DfCA pulls these automatically once connected. ELF data is retained for 24 hours by default (or 30 days with an add-on), so DfCA pulling them regularly is important.

### Salesforce Shield Logs (Require Additional Licence)

| Shield Feature | What It Adds | Which Gaps It Fills |
|---|---|---|
| **Event Monitoring** | Real-time, granular event streaming — every click, view, export as it happens | Session hijacking, field-level data access, user behaviour analytics |
| **Field Audit Trail** | Track changes to specific field values over time (up to 10 years) | Data modification history, compliance audit trail |
| **Transaction Security** | Real-time policy enforcement — block or alert during an active session | Bulk download blocking, session termination on detected anomaly |

