## 4. The MVP: Connecting Salesforce to Defender for Cloud Apps

> **📋 Before You Start — Prerequisites:**
> - A Microsoft 365 / Azure subscription with a Defender for Cloud Apps licence
> - Salesforce System Administrator access
> - Global Admin or Security Admin rights in Microsoft 365

### Step-by-Step: Setting Up the Integration

**Step 1: Open Defender for Cloud Apps Portal**
- Go to: `https://security.microsoft.com`
- Navigate to: **Cloud Apps > Connected Apps > App Connectors**
- This is the hub where you connect third-party apps like Salesforce

**Step 2: Add Salesforce as a Connected App**
- Click **"+ Connect an App"** and search for Salesforce
- Click on Salesforce, then **"Connect Salesforce"**
- You will be prompted to authenticate with your Salesforce admin credentials

> **⚠️ Important:** The Salesforce account you use to connect must be a System Administrator. DfCA needs this level of access to read audit logs and event data. Use a **dedicated service account** for this — not a personal admin account. This is best practice so the connection does not break if someone's account is modified.

**Step 3: Grant OAuth Permissions**
- Salesforce will show a permissions consent screen
- DfCA needs: Read all data, Run reports, Manage users (read), Access Audit Trail
- Click **Allow**
- DfCA will now appear as a Connected App inside Salesforce (Setup > Apps > Connected Apps)

> **💡 What is OAuth?** It is a secure way for two systems to authorise each other without sharing passwords. Salesforce "trusts" DfCA to read its logs because you explicitly approved it through this consent screen.

**Step 4: Verify the Connection**
- Back in the Defender portal, the Salesforce connector should show status **"Connected"**
- It may take up to 1 hour for the first batch of logs to appear
- Navigate to **Cloud Apps > Activity Log** and verify Salesforce events are flowing in

**Step 5: Review What Data Is Being Collected**
Once connected, DfCA automatically pulls:
- Login events (success and failure)
- Setup Audit Trail entries (admin changes)
- Event Log Files (the ~50 event categories)
- API activity

### Understanding the Defender for Cloud Apps Interface

| Section | What You Use It For |
|---|---|
| **Activity Log** | See every Salesforce event DfCA has collected. Filter by user, IP, action type, date. |
| **Alerts** | Triggered notifications when a policy is violated. This is your security inbox. |
| **Policies** | Rules that define what counts as suspicious. DfCA has built-in policies and you can create custom ones. |
| **Investigation > Users** | Profile view per user — see their activity timeline, risk score, and alerts. |

