## 8. Key Concepts Glossary

| Term | Plain English |
|---|---|
| **OAuth** | A secure way for two systems to authorise each other. DfCA uses it to access Salesforce logs without needing a shared password. |
| **API** | A way for software to talk to other software. Bad actors can abuse APIs to extract data in bulk without using the Salesforce UI. |
| **SIEM** | Security Info & Event Management — a system that collects logs from many sources and correlates them (e.g. Microsoft Sentinel, Splunk). The next step after DfCA if you need more power. |
| **MFA** | Multi-Factor Authentication — requiring a second proof of identity (e.g. a phone app code) beyond just a password. |
| **Breakglass Account** | An emergency admin account that bypasses SSO. Used only in crises. Any use must be alerted on immediately. |
| **SSO** | Single Sign-On — one login for multiple apps. Most corporate Salesforce orgs use SSO via Azure AD. Breakglass accounts bypass it. |
| **Impossible Travel** | When a user logs in from London, then 3 minutes later from Tokyo — physically impossible. Strong indicator of compromise. |
| **User Agent** | A string sent by a browser or app identifying itself. `Mozilla/5.0` is a browser. `python-requests/2.28` is a script. Unexpected scripts are suspicious. |
| **OWD (Org-Wide Defaults)** | Salesforce's baseline sharing settings — who can see what by default. Changes to OWD can expose data to the wrong people. |
| **False Positive** | An alert that fires but is not actually a threat (e.g. a legitimate bulk export triggering a mass download alert). Tuning policies reduces these. |
| **ELF (Event Log Files)** | Daily CSV log files Salesforce generates covering ~50 event types. DfCA pulls these automatically. The core log source for the MVP. |
| **DfCA** | Microsoft Defender for Cloud Apps — the tool that connects to Salesforce, monitors activity, and generates security alerts. |

